have been in the old cloud
atlases from the 1890s

00:08:52.030 --> 00:08:52.830 align:middle line:90%
and so forth.

00:08:52.830 --> 00:08:56.700 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Will there be newer
clouds as well beyond what

00:08:56.700 --> 00:08:58.060 align:middle line:90%
we just saw?

00:08:58.060 --> 00:08:59.551 align:middle line:84%
>>STEVENS: I think
it's inevitable.

00:08:59.551 --> 00:09:00.550 align:middle line:90%
I think it's inevitable.

00:09:00.550 --> 00:09:03.630 align:middle line:84%
I believe that we will discover
or already have discovered--

00:09:03.630 --> 00:09:05.820 align:middle line:84%
and maybe I just
haven't seen yet--

00:09:05.820 --> 00:09:09.690 align:middle line:84%
other technologies able to
play with the etheric field

00:09:09.690 --> 00:09:12.930 align:middle line:84%
and with scalar tech
and with acoustics.

00:09:12.930 --> 00:09:14.640 align:middle line:84%
And all these
other techs are all

00:09:14.640 --> 00:09:18.810 align:middle line:84%
going to manifest differently
in different water vapor

00:09:18.810 --> 00:09:19.830 align:middle line:90%
environments.

00:09:19.830 --> 00:09:23.370 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Scott, what
clouds create rain?

00:09:23.370 --> 00:09:24.630 align:middle line:90%
>>STEVENS: Typically nimbus.

00:09:24.630 --> 00:09:26.370 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Nimbus clouds.

00:09:26.370 --> 00:09:27.960 align:middle line:90%
Those are old-time clouds.

00:09:27.960 --> 00:09:29.760 align:middle line:84%
>>STEVENS: Yeah,
the old standby.

00:09:29.760 --> 00:09:31.490 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: With the
new ones we just saw,

00:09:31.490 --> 00:09:33.000 align:middle line:90%
will you get rain out of those?

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:33.900 align:middle line:90%
>>STEVENS: You can.

00:09:33.900 --> 00:09:34.700 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely.

00:09:34.700 --> 00:09:38.110 align:middle line:84%
If the water droplet is allowed
to form to the correct size,

00:09:38.110 --> 00:09:40.930 align:middle line:84%
the gravity will take over
and bring it out of the sky.

00:09:40.930 --> 00:09:44.610 align:middle line:84%
Now, those wave clouds
that we saw at the very end

00:09:44.610 --> 00:09:47.580 align:middle line:84%
where you have the
scalloping looks at the top--

00:09:47.580 --> 00:09:50.560 align:middle line:84%
that's simply one layer of
the atmosphere racing very,

00:09:50.560 --> 00:09:54.240 align:middle line:84%
very quickly above a static
or sometimes even retrograding

00:09:54.240 --> 00:09:55.834 align:middle line:90%
layer of the atmosphere.

00:09:55.834 --> 00:09:58.125 align:middle line:84%
And we'll look at some trails
here in a little bit that

00:09:58.125 --> 00:10:01.080 align:middle line:84%
will let you see
literally one trail moving

00:10:01.080 --> 00:10:02.730 align:middle line:90%
like this across another.

00:10:02.730 --> 00:10:05.550 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Now, you said that
these started maybe around

00:10:05.550 --> 00:10:06.540 align:middle line:90%
the '70s--

00:10:06.540 --> 00:10:08.550 align:middle line:90%
these newer versions.

00:10:08.550 --> 00:10:11.550 align:middle line:84%
What was the impetus
that started that?

00:10:11.550 --> 00:10:13.650 align:middle line:84%
>>STEVENS: And this is
speculation from the people

00:10:13.650 --> 00:10:16.600 align:middle line:84%
that I've talked with and
come across information.

00:10:16.600 --> 00:10:20.700 align:middle line:84%
It would be the globalization
of the weather modification

00:10:20.700 --> 00:10:21.740 align:middle line:90%
technology.

00:10:21.740 --> 00:10:23.700 align:middle line:84%
It would have happened
in the '50s and '60s

00:10:23.700 --> 00:10:27.150 align:middle line:84%
on a more localized basis
dealing with cloud seeding,

00:10:27.150 --> 00:10:30.450 align:middle line:84%
dealing with what may be
ground-based lasers just to see

00:10:30.450 --> 00:10:35.250 align:middle line:84%
if we can't get some kind of
precipitation or condensation

00:10:35.250 --> 00:10:37.960 align:middle line:84%
to form and to
grow large enough.

00:10:37.960 --> 00:10:41.070 align:middle line:84%
But I believe if
Colonel Bearden is right

00:10:41.070 --> 00:10:43.140 align:middle line:84%
that at some point
in the '70s, they

00:10:43.140 --> 00:10:46.050 align:middle line:84%
had the tech to do this
on a much larger scale.

00:10:46.050 --> 00:10:47.880 align:middle line:84%
And it's only
filled in the planet

00:10:47.880 --> 00:10:51.660 align:middle line:84%
sets, meaning more and more
operations have happened.

00:10:51.660 --> 00:10:53.850 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And will there be
different kinds of cloud

00:10:53.850 --> 00:10:55.357 align:middle line:90%
formations in the future?

00:10:55.357 --> 00:10:56.940 align:middle line:84%
>>STEVENS: I think
it's highly likely.

00:10:56.940 --> 00:10:57.750 align:middle line:90%
Highly likely.

00:10:57.750 --> 00:10:59.780 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I mean, how
many can we possibly get?

00:10:59.780 --> 00:11:01.155 align:middle line:84%
>>STEVENS: We
don't want to know.

00:11:01.155 --> 00:11:02.130 align:middle line:90%
We don't want to.

00:11:02.130 --> 00:11:02.910 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: How many were there?

00:11:02.910 --> 00:11:03.170 align:middle line:90%
Nine?

00:11:03.170 --> 00:11:04.420 align:middle line:90%
>>STEVENS: Well, they said 12.

00:11:04.420 --> 00:11:06.120 align:middle line:90%
And we saw pictures of four.

00:11:06.120 --> 00:11:07.120 align:middle line:90%
We saw pictures of four.

00:11:07.120 --> 00:11:09.036 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And how many
did we have in the past?

00:11:09.036 --> 00:11:11.280 align:middle line:84%
In the original
cloud formations--

00:11:11.280 --> 00:11:12.930 align:middle line:90%
the cumulus, the nimbus--

00:11:12.930 --> 00:11:14.257 align:middle line:90%
what did we have, four or five?

00:11:14.257 --> 00:11:15.840 align:middle line:84%
>>STEVENS: On the
old cloud pictures--

00:11:15.840 --> 00:11:19.440 align:middle line:84%
I had one up on my wall
and studying scouts,

00:11:19.440 --> 00:11:21.240 align:middle line:84%
just like in geophysical
and weather stuff.

00:11:21.240 --> 00:11:25.080 align:middle line:84%
There were probably 90 to 100
different kinds of cirruses,

00:11:25.080 --> 00:11:26.880 align:middle line:90%
different kinds of cumulus--

00:11:26.880 --> 00:11:29.970 align:middle line:84%
small, fair-weather
cumulus to the cumulonimbus

00:11:29.970 --> 00:11:31.890 align:middle line:84%
that eventually
develop thunderstorms--

00:11:31.890 --> 00:11:34.860 align:middle line:84%
the stratus and then how that
becomes a cirrostratus, which

00:11:34.860 --> 00:11:38.760 align:middle line:84%
is stratus up higher and then
becomes a low-cloud fog just

00:11:38.760 --> 00:11:39.660 align:middle line:90%
off the ground.

00:11:39.660 --> 00:11:41.618 align:middle line:84%
All of these different
layers of the atmosphere

00:11:41.618 --> 00:11:44.040 align:middle line:84%
have different cloud
manifestations.

00:11:44.040 --> 00:11:46.200 align:middle line:84%
But when you begin
to add electricity,

00:11:46.200 --> 00:11:48.760 align:middle line:90%
magnetism, particulates--

00:11:48.760 --> 00:11:49.560 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Pollution.

00:11:49.560 --> 00:11:51.210 align:middle line:84%
>>STEVENS:
--pollution, obviously.

00:11:51.210 --> 00:11:52.720 align:middle line:90%
That's a part of it.

00:11:52.720 --> 00:11:55.950 align:middle line:84%
And then there's all these
other invisible forces--

00:11:55.950 --> 00:11:57.540 align:middle line:90%
these invisible forces.

00:11:57.540 --> 00:12:00.480 align:middle line:84%
Tesla said, once man
begins to investigate

00:12:00.480 --> 00:12:02.910 align:middle line:84%
the invisible, in
10 years, he'll

00:12:02.910 --> 00:12:05.520 align:middle line:84%
learn more than
the previous 100.

00:12:05.520 --> 00:12:08.960 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I want to talk to
you about hail for a moment.

00:12:08.960 --> 00:12:11.020 align:middle line:90%
Why is it so rare?

00:12:11.020 --> 00:12:13.150 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't happen a lot.

00:12:13.150 --> 00:12:15.520 align:middle line:84%
You would think that
it would and that we'd

00:12:15.520 --> 00:12:18.190 align:middle line:90%
be pelted by brick-size hail.

00:12:18.190 --> 00:12:19.500 align:middle line:90%
We're not all the time.

00:12:19.500 --> 00:12:21.700 align:middle line:90%
Where is it coming from?

00:12:21.700 --> 00:12:24.310 align:middle line:84%
>>STEVENS: There's a couple
of ways to approach this.

00:12:24.310 --> 00:12:28.960 align:middle line:84%
Hail is more regular at
certain latitudes than others.

00:12:28.960 --> 00:12:32.140 align:middle line:84%
You tend to have them, say,
on the front range of Colorado

00:12:32.140 --> 00:12:34.540 align:middle line:84%
or out into the
plains during spring.

00:12:34.540 --> 00:12:37.450 align:middle line:84%
During the springtime when the
freezing level is still low,

00:12:37.450 --> 00:12:39.670 align:middle line:84%
you still get the turbulence
or the violent updrafts.

00:12:39.670 --> 00:12:42.460 align:middle line:84%
And then that water molecule
ices over and melts,

00:12:42.460 --> 00:12:44.500 align:middle line:84%
and you get this
looping going on.

00:12:44.500 --> 00:12:46.300 align:middle line:84%
But what I've also
seen is thunderstorms,

00:12:46.300 --> 00:12:49.450 align:middle line:84%
instead of developing vertically
or slightly at a slant,

00:12:49.450 --> 00:12:54.220 align:middle line:84%
are tipped over like
this as that wave cloud.

00:12:54.220 --> 00:12:57.130 align:middle line:84%
We're seeing tops of the
atmosphere rolling very, very

00:12:57.130 --> 00:12:59.810 align:middle line:84%
fast and the bottom moving
in a different direction.

00:12:59.810 --> 00:13:03.130 align:middle line:84%
So what this happens is that
you can have a thunderstorm that

00:13:03.130 --> 00:13:07.050 align:middle line:84%
at the top, the radar only sees
it at maybe 35,000 feet where

00:13:07.050 --> 00:13:09.850 align:middle line:84%
in the old days it might
have been a 45,000-foot top.

00:13:09.850 --> 00:13:11.830 align:middle line:84%
But the length is
actually extended.

00:13:11.830 --> 00:13:14.380 align:middle line:84%
And the whole
thing is spiraling.

00:13:14.380 --> 00:13:17.950 align:middle line:84%
And so you can have in
this electrical field--

00:13:17.950 --> 00:13:20.380 align:middle line:84%
because once you get
ice and water rotating,

00:13:20.380 --> 00:13:23.500 align:middle line:84%
you're going to create a current
and an electrical suspension

00:13:23.500 --> 00:13:24.860 align:middle line:90%
field as well.

00:13:24.860 --> 00:13:27.175 align:middle line:84%
So then you can get
hail larger and larger.

00:13:27.175 --> 00:13:31.836 align:middle line:84%
So there may be places
that see less hail simply

00:13:31.836 --> 00:13:33.460 align:middle line:84%
because they're under
a drought agenda.

00:13:33.460 --> 00:13:36.920 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What's the biggest
hail you've ever seen?

00:13:36.920 --> 00:13:39.950 align:middle line:84%
>>STEVENS: A little bit larger
than golf ball, and that hurt.

00:13:39.950 --> 00:13:40.750 align:middle line:90%
That hurt.

00:13:40.750 --> 00:13:43.899 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I mean, that could bust
a windshield of a car, right?

00:13:43.899 --> 00:13:46.065 align:middle line:84%
>>STEVENS: And if you're a
gardener, you're crying--

00:13:46.065 --> 00:13:46.320 align:middle line:90%
or a farmer.

00:13:46.320 --> 00:13:47.800 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: If you get
hit by one of these.

00:13:47.800 --> 00:13:48.970 align:middle line:90%
They're ice balls, right?

00:13:48.970 --> 00:13:50.428 align:middle line:84%
>>STEVENS: Yeah,
they're ice balls.

00:13:50.428 --> 00:13:52.430 align:middle line:84%
And you're watching
your crops shredded--

00:13:52.430 --> 00:13:53.380 align:middle line:90%
shredded.

00:13:53.380 --> 00:13:57.100 align:middle line:84%
And it is a very
dangerous-- and I don't want

00:13:57.100 --> 00:13:58.780 align:middle line:90%
to say it's easy to create.

00:13:58.780 --> 00:14:01.360 align:middle line:84%
But with this tech, you
can create those things.

00:14:01.360 --> 00:14:05.230 align:middle line:84%
You can create devastating
swaths of thunderstorms

00:14:05.230 --> 00:14:07.360 align:middle line:90%
that just strip fields.

00:14:07.360 --> 00:14:11.740 align:middle line:84%
And corn hit in second week
of August by a hailstorm--

00:14:11.740 --> 00:14:13.130 align:middle line:90%
it's tough to recover from.

00:14:13.130 --> 00:14:15.040 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I had a roof
repaired once, Scotty,

00:14:15.040 --> 00:14:18.920 align:middle line:84%
because hail damaged
it over the years.

00:14:18.920 --> 00:14:20.560 align:middle line:90%
I called my insurance company.

00:14:20.560 --> 00:14:24.100 align:middle line:84%
And a guy came out and
said, this roof is totaled.

00:14:24.100 --> 00:14:28.540 align:middle line:84%
And it had been pelted
over the years with hail.

00:14:28.540 --> 00:14:29.780 align:middle line:90%
That's pretty damaging stuff.

00:14:29.780 --> 00:14:30.580 align:middle line:90%
>>STEVENS: It is.

00:14:30.580 --> 00:14:32.440 align:middle line:84%
And if you had a
composite roof--

00:14:32.440 --> 00:14:35.540 align:middle line:84%
the asphalt one-- it's
good for about 20 years.

00:14:35.540 --> 00:14:37.560 align:middle line:84%
But if you hit it with
hail numerous times--

00:14:37.560 --> 00:14:38.140 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Bang.

00:14:38.140 --> 00:14:38.940 align:middle line:90%
>>STEVENS: Yeah.

00:14:38.940 --> 00:14:41.230 align:middle line:90%
It's like tenderizing meat.

00:14:41.230 --> 00:14:43.150 align:middle line:90%
It turns to mush quickly.

00:14:43.150 --> 00:14:45.640 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: There is a controversy
over something called

00:14:45.640 --> 00:14:46.532 align:middle line:90%
chemtrails.

00:14:46.532 --> 00:14:47.990 align:middle line:84%
>>STEVENS: I haven't
heard of them.

00:14:47.990 --> 00:14:49.510 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: What are they?

00:14:49.510 --> 00:14:50.890 align:middle line:90%
Where do they come from?

00:14:50.890 --> 00:14:52.750 align:middle line:90%
What's going on?

00:14:52.750 --> 00:14:54.920 align:middle line:90%
I'll give you an example.

00:14:54.920 --> 00:14:57.040 align:middle line:84%
You may wake up in the
morning, and the skies

00:14:57.040 --> 00:14:59.080 align:middle line:90%
are perfectly clear.

00:14:59.080 --> 00:15:02.500 align:middle line:84%
Later in the afternoon, you
see these tic-tac-toe patterns

00:15:02.500 --> 00:15:04.220 align:middle line:90%
everywhere.

00:15:04.220 --> 00:15:06.440 align:middle line:90%
It's not just jet vapor.

00:15:06.440 --> 00:15:10.780 align:middle line:84%
It's not just the fuel
residual from jets.

00:15:10.780 --> 00:15:12.640 align:middle line:84%
Those patterns aren't
there every day.

00:15:12.640 --> 00:15:15.190 align:middle line:84%
They would be because these
planes fly the same direction

00:15:15.190 --> 00:15:16.146 align:middle line:90%
all the time.

00:15:16.146 --> 00:15:17.500 align:middle line:90%
What are they?

00:15:17.500 --> 00:15:19.510 align:middle line:90%
What are chemtrails?

00:15:19.510 --> 00:15:22.780 align:middle line:84%
>>STEVENS: As I got into my
geoengineering rabbit hole,

00:15:22.780 --> 00:15:25.710 align:middle line:84%
I didn't realize it was
going to be so large.

00:15:25.710 --> 00:15:29.340 align:middle line:84%
And I came to terms with
clouds and pictures--

00:15:29.340 --> 00:15:30.900 align:middle line:90%
and we'll see some in a bit--

00:15:30.900 --> 00:15:34.570 align:middle line:84%
that there were shapes and
clouds that shouldn't be there.

00:15:34.570 --> 00:15:39.600 align:middle line:84%
But then the next step was, how
do they organize the weather

00:15:39.600 --> 00:15:41.580 align:middle line:90%
that they're creating?

00:15:41.580 --> 00:15:43.929 align:middle line:84%
And it took some time-lapse
cameras on my part

00:15:43.929 --> 00:15:45.470 align:middle line:84%
and some computers
and some software.

00:15:45.470 --> 00:15:46.553 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: You're convinced.

00:15:46.553 --> 00:15:48.240 align:middle line:84%
>>STEVENS: I just
needed to know.

00:15:48.240 --> 00:15:49.230 align:middle line:90%
I needed to know.

00:15:49.230 --> 00:15:51.180 align:middle line:84%
And I was on the
air at the time,

00:15:51.180 --> 00:15:53.900 align:middle line:84%
and I still had a
responsibility to an audience.

00:15:53.900 --> 00:15:57.220 align:middle line:84%
And I didn't like coming on and
saying, I goofed a forecast.

00:15:57.220 --> 00:15:58.240 align:middle line:90%
My bad.

00:15:58.240 --> 00:15:59.790 align:middle line:90%
But it wasn't my bad.

00:15:59.790 --> 00:16:01.890 align:middle line:84%
The storm didn't perform
as it was modeled

00:16:01.890 --> 00:16:03.350 align:middle line:90%
and historically would have.

00:16:03.350 --> 00:16:04.600 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It was unpredictable.

00:16:04.600 --> 00:16:06.554 align:middle line:84%
>>STEVENS: Something
was going on.

00:16:06.554 --> 00:16:08.970 align:middle line:84%
So I put these cameras up just
to see what the clouds were

00:16:08.970 --> 00:16:10.740 align:middle line:90%
doing that I was missing.

00:16:10.740 --> 00:16:12.240 align:middle line:84%
Is there something
that I can catch?

00:16:12.240 --> 00:16:17.470 align:middle line:84%
And then I can give my audience
a more genuine forecast.

00:16:17.470 --> 00:16:19.440 align:middle line:84%
But it was the chemtrails
that showed up.

00:16:19.440 --> 00:16:21.330 align:middle line:90%
And there were patterns.

00:16:21.330 --> 00:16:23.615 align:middle line:84%
The trail would come along,
leave a little bit of it,

00:16:23.615 --> 00:16:25.740 align:middle line:84%
and then another one would
come along and hit right

00:16:25.740 --> 00:16:27.850 align:middle line:84%
at the middle of that
little leftover trail that

00:16:27.850 --> 00:16:29.910 align:middle line:90%
was there or hit it at the end.

00:16:29.910 --> 00:16:32.960 align:middle line:84%
Or the trail spread
a little part of it.

00:16:32.960 --> 00:16:35.520 align:middle line:84%
And then another plane
came along exactly

00:16:35.520 --> 00:16:38.370 align:middle line:84%
and hit it precisely at the
direction it was spreading.

00:16:38.370 --> 00:16:40.560 align:middle line:84%
And I'm like no, no,
no, no, no, no, no.

00:16:40.560 --> 00:16:41.730 align:middle line:90%
I see.

00:16:41.730 --> 00:16:43.440 align:middle line:90%
I see what they're doing.

00:16:43.440 --> 00:16:46.050 align:middle line:84%
They're sculpting the
weather in real time

00:16:46.050 --> 00:16:47.740 align:middle line:90%
by where these planes are.

00:16:47.740 --> 00:16:48.540 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: But why?

00:16:48.540 --> 00:16:50.123 align:middle line:84%
>>STEVENS: And they
just leave a trail

00:16:50.123 --> 00:16:52.067 align:middle line:84%
to figure out what the
heck they're doing.

00:16:52.067 --> 00:16:53.400 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Are they experimenting?

00:16:53.400 --> 00:16:54.816 align:middle line:84%
>>STEVENS: Oh, no,
no, no, no, no.

00:16:54.816 --> 00:16:56.040 align:middle line:90%
That was the '60s and '70s.

00:16:56.040 --> 00:16:57.020 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So they know
what they're doing now.

00:16:57.020 --> 00:16:57.850 align:middle line:84%
>>STEVENS: We're
full-on operation.

00:16:57.850 --> 00:16:59.058 align:middle line:90%
They know what they're doing.

00:16:59.058 --> 00:17:02.996 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I always remember when
the Chinese had the Olympics.

00:17:02.996 --> 00:17:05.579 align:middle line:84%
And somebody said, what are you
going to do about the weather?

00:17:05.579 --> 00:17:08.250 align:middle line:84%
And they went, we
control the weather.

00:17:08.250 --> 00:17:09.907 align:middle line:84%
That was an
incredible revelation.

