00:25:27.080 --> 00:25:29.880 align:middle line:84%
like it was such a
brief period in time.

00:25:29.880 --> 00:25:31.070 align:middle line:90%
Because I went public--

00:25:31.070 --> 00:25:34.910 align:middle line:84%
I published to a blog in
October of '04, and I was let go

00:25:34.910 --> 00:25:35.909 align:middle line:90%
in September of '05.

00:25:35.909 --> 00:25:36.950 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Because of that.

00:25:36.950 --> 00:25:38.075 align:middle line:90%
>>STEVENS: Because of that.

00:25:38.075 --> 00:25:40.370 align:middle line:90%


00:25:40.370 --> 00:25:41.860 align:middle line:90%
I used my KPVI.

00:25:41.860 --> 00:25:45.410 align:middle line:84%
I used the call letters when I
set it off and got published.

00:25:45.410 --> 00:25:46.369 align:middle line:90%
You kind of have to.

00:25:46.369 --> 00:25:48.410 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: See, I would
have-- as a news director--

00:25:48.410 --> 00:25:51.620 align:middle line:84%
would have relished the fact
that my weather caster was

00:25:51.620 --> 00:25:53.420 align:middle line:84%
getting some
national publicity--

00:25:53.420 --> 00:25:54.000 align:middle line:90%
>>STEVENS: You would think.

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:55.250 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: --on stuff like that.

00:25:55.250 --> 00:25:56.126 align:middle line:90%
I would have used it.

00:25:56.126 --> 00:25:56.925 align:middle line:90%
>>STEVENS: Yep.

00:25:56.925 --> 00:25:59.110 align:middle line:84%
And that could have gone
a very different way--

00:25:59.110 --> 00:26:00.680 align:middle line:90%
the whole evolvement.

00:26:00.680 --> 00:26:03.770 align:middle line:84%
But what I still didn't
know at that point in time

00:26:03.770 --> 00:26:07.880 align:middle line:84%
was how it was being
done, the technology used,

00:26:07.880 --> 00:26:11.270 align:middle line:84%
the extent of the trails,
how they played in.

00:26:11.270 --> 00:26:13.830 align:middle line:84%
I had only the most
basic of outline

00:26:13.830 --> 00:26:17.000 align:middle line:84%
to know that what
I was forecasting

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:19.280 align:middle line:90%
wasn't what I was forecasting.

00:26:19.280 --> 00:26:21.920 align:middle line:84%
There's a whole other agenda
that I was not privy to,

00:26:21.920 --> 00:26:23.990 align:middle line:84%
whether it was to
rain or to snow.

00:26:23.990 --> 00:26:27.350 align:middle line:84%
What I did learn was,
forecast the trend.

00:26:27.350 --> 00:26:31.700 align:middle line:84%
Whatever is happening-- if it
looks like it's going to rain,

00:26:31.700 --> 00:26:33.200 align:middle line:84%
this is just a
little bit of a spit.

00:26:33.200 --> 00:26:35.180 align:middle line:84%
And we're not going to
get much out of this.

00:26:35.180 --> 00:26:37.370 align:middle line:84%
And go with the
trend, and you'll

00:26:37.370 --> 00:26:39.050 align:middle line:90%
out-forecast all your peers.

00:26:39.050 --> 00:26:41.960 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Is it difficult
today for weather forecasters

00:26:41.960 --> 00:26:43.190 align:middle line:90%
to predict the weather?

00:26:43.190 --> 00:26:45.190 align:middle line:84%
>>STEVENS: It's painful
for me to watch them.

00:26:45.190 --> 00:26:46.310 align:middle line:90%
It really is.

00:26:46.310 --> 00:26:48.530 align:middle line:90%
It really is-- to watch them.

00:26:48.530 --> 00:26:52.440 align:middle line:84%
And the graphics they
put up are cartoonish.

00:26:52.440 --> 00:26:53.630 align:middle line:90%
There's no resolution.

00:26:53.630 --> 00:26:55.190 align:middle line:90%
There's no details.

00:26:55.190 --> 00:26:57.520 align:middle line:84%
It's like the bubbly
forecaster showing us

00:26:57.520 --> 00:26:59.360 align:middle line:90%
the shiny new clouds.

00:26:59.360 --> 00:27:00.710 align:middle line:90%
It's a facade.

00:27:00.710 --> 00:27:02.330 align:middle line:90%
The science is gone.

00:27:02.330 --> 00:27:05.250 align:middle line:84%
It's a facade to play to
the "Entertainment Tonight"

00:27:05.250 --> 00:27:06.050 align:middle line:90%
community.

00:27:06.050 --> 00:27:07.190 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Exactly.

00:27:07.190 --> 00:27:08.840 align:middle line:90%
I mean, I do my own forecasting.

00:27:08.840 --> 00:27:10.810 align:middle line:90%
I'm not a weather forecaster.

00:27:10.810 --> 00:27:12.590 align:middle line:90%
I'll look at a radar map.

00:27:12.590 --> 00:27:16.520 align:middle line:84%
And I'll see that over
Colorado, there's rain.

00:27:16.520 --> 00:27:19.520 align:middle line:84%
And then I'll predict
the speed of that.

00:27:19.520 --> 00:27:22.520 align:middle line:84%
And I'll say, this is going to
hit St. Louis in three days.

00:27:22.520 --> 00:27:25.110 align:middle line:84%
We're going to have rain in
three days, and I'm right.

00:27:25.110 --> 00:27:25.910 align:middle line:90%
>>STEVENS: Yeah.

00:27:25.910 --> 00:27:28.286 align:middle line:84%
And as that storm would leave
the west and head out east,

00:27:28.286 --> 00:27:30.618 align:middle line:84%
you're going to assume we're
going to get to south wind.

00:27:30.618 --> 00:27:32.270 align:middle line:84%
The moisture will
be caught up in it.

00:27:32.270 --> 00:27:33.769 align:middle line:84%
That thing will
continue to develop.

00:27:33.769 --> 00:27:35.330 align:middle line:90%
It's all logical.

00:27:35.330 --> 00:27:37.160 align:middle line:90%
It's training.

00:27:37.160 --> 00:27:38.600 align:middle line:90%
There's a little science.

00:27:38.600 --> 00:27:41.750 align:middle line:84%
But when you get to the TV
aspect of it, it's training.

00:27:41.750 --> 00:27:44.750 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: In your opinion,
why modify the weather?

00:27:44.750 --> 00:27:46.460 align:middle line:90%
>>STEVENS: Because you can.

00:27:46.460 --> 00:27:47.840 align:middle line:90%
Because you can.

00:27:47.840 --> 00:27:49.850 align:middle line:84%
And that way, it becomes
a tool for somebody

00:27:49.850 --> 00:27:52.680 align:middle line:90%
who will give you the money.

00:27:52.680 --> 00:27:53.480 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:27:53.480 --> 00:27:56.840 align:middle line:84%
I really believe there's
a darkness on this planet.

00:27:56.840 --> 00:27:59.840 align:middle line:84%
And they're the ones that
have co-opted these programs.

00:27:59.840 --> 00:28:01.850 align:middle line:84%
They may have been the
ones that were even

00:28:01.850 --> 00:28:04.970 align:middle line:84%
the inspiration for the program
if we go to Project Paperclip

00:28:04.970 --> 00:28:08.280 align:middle line:84%
and bringing back
scientists from Germany,

00:28:08.280 --> 00:28:09.160 align:middle line:90%
from World War II.

00:28:09.160 --> 00:28:11.840 align:middle line:10%
And you get those
minds over here

00:28:11.840 --> 00:28:14.840 align:middle line:10%
plus what we were working
on, and you get it together.

00:28:14.840 --> 00:28:16.340 align:middle line:10%
There's nothing
like a bunch of guys

00:28:16.340 --> 00:28:18.050 align:middle line:10%
getting together and
coming up with ideas

00:28:18.050 --> 00:28:19.640 align:middle line:10%
and fantastic things.

00:28:19.640 --> 00:28:22.610 align:middle line:84%
And then corporations
and governments

00:28:22.610 --> 00:28:24.342 align:middle line:90%
are willing to write a check.

00:28:24.342 --> 00:28:26.300 align:middle line:84%
Because if they don't
have to share the secrets

00:28:26.300 --> 00:28:30.870 align:middle line:84%
with the people,
that we can do this,

00:28:30.870 --> 00:28:34.320 align:middle line:84%
then it's kind of like
an orgy of science.

00:28:34.320 --> 00:28:36.860 align:middle line:90%
That's exciting.

00:28:36.860 --> 00:28:42.020 align:middle line:84%
When they give the tools over
to the military or to the users,

00:28:42.020 --> 00:28:43.700 align:middle line:90%
will there be culpability?

00:28:43.700 --> 00:28:46.550 align:middle line:10%
Will there be responsibility
and accountability?

00:28:46.550 --> 00:28:48.170 align:middle line:10%
Will there be
eventually sunshine

00:28:48.170 --> 00:28:52.820 align:middle line:10%
on these projects that were
shepherded 60, 70 years ago?

00:28:52.820 --> 00:28:54.870 align:middle line:90%
When does that happen?

00:28:54.870 --> 00:28:56.510 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: What's global dimming?

00:28:56.510 --> 00:29:00.140 align:middle line:84%
>>STEVENS: Global dimming--
that kind of came into vogue

00:29:00.140 --> 00:29:01.214 align:middle line:90%
about 20 years ago.

00:29:01.214 --> 00:29:02.630 align:middle line:84%
And we've even
launched satellites

00:29:02.630 --> 00:29:07.070 align:middle line:84%
to go find the aerosols that
seem to be in the sky dimming

00:29:07.070 --> 00:29:08.480 align:middle line:90%
the sunshine.

00:29:08.480 --> 00:29:10.730 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Do they just hang
up there and loom up there?

00:29:10.730 --> 00:29:12.440 align:middle line:84%
>>STEVENS: Yeah,
they're just suspended.

00:29:12.440 --> 00:29:15.290 align:middle line:84%
And we end up with these
kind of milky-white days.

00:29:15.290 --> 00:29:17.820 align:middle line:84%
The sky is blue, but
we started earlier.

00:29:17.820 --> 00:29:20.720 align:middle line:84%
It gets a little
hazier and hazier.

00:29:20.720 --> 00:29:22.280 align:middle line:84%
We tried to launch
two satellites

00:29:22.280 --> 00:29:25.890 align:middle line:84%
to find out where these
aerosols were coming from.

00:29:25.890 --> 00:29:27.159 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: We don't know?

00:29:27.159 --> 00:29:28.200 align:middle line:90%
>>STEVENS: Good question.

00:29:28.200 --> 00:29:30.500 align:middle line:84%
Well, they were looking
for point sources.

00:29:30.500 --> 00:29:32.060 align:middle line:90%
Is it industry in China?

00:29:32.060 --> 00:29:34.070 align:middle line:90%
Is it industry in India?

00:29:34.070 --> 00:29:37.140 align:middle line:84%
Is it manufacturing, or is it
the natural gas production?

00:29:37.140 --> 00:29:37.940 align:middle line:90%
Is it fracking?

00:29:37.940 --> 00:29:39.340 align:middle line:90%
We don't know.

00:29:39.340 --> 00:29:43.280 align:middle line:84%
So the first two satellites
failed to reach orbit.

00:29:43.280 --> 00:29:44.480 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Oh, really.

00:29:44.480 --> 00:29:45.317 align:middle line:90%
How convenient.

00:29:45.317 --> 00:29:46.400 align:middle line:90%
>>STEVENS: How convenient.

00:29:46.400 --> 00:29:48.350 align:middle line:84%
So there is something
that they didn't

00:29:48.350 --> 00:29:51.630 align:middle line:84%
want discovered about where
are these aerosols were coming

00:29:51.630 --> 00:29:52.430 align:middle line:90%
from.

00:29:52.430 --> 00:29:56.000 align:middle line:84%
And that was the early
part of this decade when

00:29:56.000 --> 00:29:57.380 align:middle line:90%
those failed to make orbit.

00:29:57.380 --> 00:30:00.140 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It seems like then
you're dealing with two

00:30:00.140 --> 00:30:01.820 align:middle line:90%
different factions--

00:30:01.820 --> 00:30:05.580 align:middle line:84%
factions that know what's going
on because they're doing it

00:30:05.580 --> 00:30:09.306 align:middle line:84%
and another faction that is not
part of it trying to figure out

00:30:09.306 --> 00:30:10.430 align:middle line:90%
what the heck is happening.

00:30:10.430 --> 00:30:11.460 align:middle line:90%
>>STEVENS: I agree.

00:30:11.460 --> 00:30:12.260 align:middle line:90%
I agree.

00:30:12.260 --> 00:30:14.240 align:middle line:84%
And so I think they've
compartmentalized

00:30:14.240 --> 00:30:15.410 align:middle line:90%
the scientific community.

00:30:15.410 --> 00:30:18.080 align:middle line:84%
They've compartmentalized
whether it's

00:30:18.080 --> 00:30:21.710 align:middle line:84%
solar research versus
atmospheric chemistry

00:30:21.710 --> 00:30:25.040 align:middle line:84%
versus cloud physics
versus modeling

00:30:25.040 --> 00:30:30.990 align:middle line:84%
versus public outreach versus
oceanography versus climate

00:30:30.990 --> 00:30:31.790 align:middle line:90%
science.

00:30:31.790 --> 00:30:34.670 align:middle line:84%
So when you have
all of these boxes,

00:30:34.670 --> 00:30:36.950 align:middle line:84%
only the people at
the top of the pyramid

00:30:36.950 --> 00:30:38.810 align:middle line:84%
are going to be able
to put it all together

00:30:38.810 --> 00:30:40.250 align:middle line:90%
for their own purposes.

00:30:40.250 --> 00:30:43.160 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Is this modification
program worldwide?

00:30:43.160 --> 00:30:44.222 align:middle line:90%
>>STEVENS: Absolutely.

00:30:44.222 --> 00:30:45.680 align:middle line:84%
Again, we're going
to go back early

00:30:45.680 --> 00:30:48.290 align:middle line:84%
on when we started
throwing rocks in the pond.

00:30:48.290 --> 00:30:51.320 align:middle line:84%
The first rock goes in,
easy to see the ripple.

00:30:51.320 --> 00:30:53.840 align:middle line:84%
The second, the third, and
the fourth, and the fifth,

00:30:53.840 --> 00:30:57.590 align:middle line:84%
it begins to contaminate
the entire planet.

00:30:57.590 --> 00:31:00.620 align:middle line:84%
And another question I got about
that were these trails in China

00:31:00.620 --> 00:31:02.030 align:middle line:90%
and Russia.

00:31:02.030 --> 00:31:03.680 align:middle line:84%
If you get a flight
tracking app,

00:31:03.680 --> 00:31:06.950 align:middle line:84%
like Flightradar24,
spend the $3.

00:31:06.950 --> 00:31:08.820 align:middle line:90%
Get the upgraded version.

00:31:08.820 --> 00:31:09.620 align:middle line:90%
It's cheap.

00:31:09.620 --> 00:31:11.990 align:middle line:84%
It's cheap compared to what
software cost 20 years ago.

00:31:11.990 --> 00:31:13.010 align:middle line:90%
It's cheap.

00:31:13.010 --> 00:31:15.530 align:middle line:84%
And you can see how
many of these planes

00:31:15.530 --> 00:31:19.070 align:middle line:84%
will fly from the United
Arab Emirates to London.

00:31:19.070 --> 00:31:22.700 align:middle line:90%


00:31:22.700 --> 00:31:25.160 align:middle line:84%
There's all these
great circle routes.

00:31:25.160 --> 00:31:28.370 align:middle line:84%
So there's all of our
Western aircraft flying

00:31:28.370 --> 00:31:32.900 align:middle line:84%
across China and Russia and
all these other seemingly

00:31:32.900 --> 00:31:34.340 align:middle line:90%
independent nations.

00:31:34.340 --> 00:31:36.870 align:middle line:84%
So they're subject to
these actions as well.

00:31:36.870 --> 00:31:39.230 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So with
this global dimming,

00:31:39.230 --> 00:31:40.955 align:middle line:84%
does it have to do
with solar cycles?

00:31:40.955 --> 00:31:43.850 align:middle line:90%


00:31:43.850 --> 00:31:45.970 align:middle line:84%
>>STEVENS: That's something
that's been looked at.

00:31:45.970 --> 00:31:48.770 align:middle line:84%
The main part of that
would be cosmic rays

00:31:48.770 --> 00:31:54.360 align:middle line:84%
and how activity on the sun
can then spark cloud growth

00:31:54.360 --> 00:31:56.810 align:middle line:84%
and if those additional
clouds would change

00:31:56.810 --> 00:32:00.020 align:middle line:84%
the reflectivity of those clouds
and the solar energy going back

00:32:00.020 --> 00:32:01.800 align:middle line:90%
into space.

00:32:01.800 --> 00:32:04.220 align:middle line:90%
So there's a yes and no.

00:32:04.220 --> 00:32:06.620 align:middle line:84%
And part of that is, there's
this block of science.

00:32:06.620 --> 00:32:08.780 align:middle line:84%
We talked about
cloud physics and how

00:32:08.780 --> 00:32:11.630 align:middle line:84%
that plays into the solar
scientists over here.

00:32:11.630 --> 00:32:15.260 align:middle line:84%
So we need to kind of get these
people all on the same page

00:32:15.260 --> 00:32:17.690 align:middle line:84%
and working on the
same papers so we

00:32:17.690 --> 00:32:19.959 align:middle line:84%
can get more definitive
answers with these things.

00:32:19.959 --> 00:32:21.500 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And Scott,
while we continue

00:32:21.500 --> 00:32:24.260 align:middle line:84%
talking about global
dimming, there

00:32:24.260 --> 00:32:29.090 align:middle line:84%
are a lot of graphs that, of
course, point that out to us.

00:32:29.090 --> 00:32:30.440 align:middle line:90%
Explain this for us.

00:32:30.440 --> 00:32:31.850 align:middle line:90%
>>STEVENS: This is solar cycles.

00:32:31.850 --> 00:32:33.680 align:middle line:84%
This is going to come
into the play of,

00:32:33.680 --> 00:32:36.350 align:middle line:84%
might the sun have anything
to do with long-term climate

00:32:36.350 --> 00:32:36.770 align:middle line:90%
trends?

00:32:36.770 --> 00:32:37.580 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And we think it does.

00:32:37.580 --> 00:32:39.079 align:middle line:84%
>>STEVENS: We kind
of believe we do,

00:32:39.079 --> 00:32:42.320 align:middle line:84%
since we were able to associate
the Maunder minimum back

00:32:42.320 --> 00:32:46.142 align:middle line:84%
in the 1600, 1700s with a
period of virtually no sunspots.

00:32:46.142 --> 00:32:47.600 align:middle line:84%
And there was a
little mini ice age

00:32:47.600 --> 00:32:50.720 align:middle line:84%
that correlated rather
nicely with that.

00:32:50.720 --> 00:32:53.400 align:middle line:84%
It looked like a
causation event.

00:32:53.400 --> 00:32:57.740 align:middle line:10%
And so what we're seeing here
are the last four solar cycles,

00:32:57.740 --> 00:33:00.440 align:middle line:10%
the blue being the oldest one--
the key is in the upper right--

00:33:00.440 --> 00:33:02.409 align:middle line:10%
from 1976 to '86.

00:33:02.409 --> 00:33:03.700 align:middle line:10%
That's when I got into weather.

00:33:03.700 --> 00:33:05.810 align:middle line:10%
And the sun was very active.

00:33:05.810 --> 00:33:07.310 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: What do
you mean by active?

00:33:07.310 --> 00:33:09.030 align:middle line:10%
>>STEVENS: The
count of sunspots.

00:33:09.030 --> 00:33:11.300 align:middle line:10%
And so what we're
looking at on this chart

00:33:11.300 --> 00:33:15.660 align:middle line:10%
is the number of sunspots
counted in a single month.

00:33:15.660 --> 00:33:19.220 align:middle line:10%
So we'll take 12 months and
add them up, do an average,

00:33:19.220 --> 00:33:20.750 align:middle line:10%
and then that's the number.

00:33:20.750 --> 00:33:23.480 align:middle line:10%
So we were running
in the 200s back

00:33:23.480 --> 00:33:24.921 align:middle line:10%
in the '70s and early '80s.

00:33:24.921 --> 00:33:26.670 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: Explain what
a sunspot is for me.

00:33:26.670 --> 00:33:28.820 align:middle line:10%
>>STEVENS: It's a magnetic
storm on the sun--

00:33:28.820 --> 00:33:31.160 align:middle line:10%
a place that is
cooler because we're

00:33:31.160 --> 00:33:34.850 align:middle line:10%
having an inflowing
of ejecta-- well,

00:33:34.850 --> 00:33:36.860 align:middle line:10%
actually, material--
into the sunspot.

00:33:36.860 --> 00:33:39.140 align:middle line:84%
And there's this
circulation pattern.

00:33:39.140 --> 00:33:41.270 align:middle line:84%
So it turns over the
surface of the sun

00:33:41.270 --> 00:33:44.574 align:middle line:84%
and brings up substance and
energy and matter from below.

00:33:44.574 --> 00:33:45.740 align:middle line:90%
So it's an event of the sun.

00:33:45.740 --> 00:33:47.490 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And if there
are lot of sunspots,

00:33:47.490 --> 00:33:49.970 align:middle line:84%
that means generally we're
going to have cooler climate?

00:33:49.970 --> 00:33:51.500 align:middle line:90%
>>STEVENS: Warmer climate.

00:33:51.500 --> 00:33:52.490 align:middle line:90%
Warmer climate.

00:33:52.490 --> 00:33:54.269 align:middle line:84%
We're active, so more
energy is coming--

00:33:54.269 --> 00:33:56.060 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Even though
the sunspot is cooler.

00:33:56.060 --> 00:33:57.230 align:middle line:90%
>>STEVENS: Thank you.

00:33:57.230 --> 00:33:59.000 align:middle line:84%
There's that much
more energy that it's

